Kroger Supermarket R550 – Traffic Impact Analysis
The traffic impacts of the proposed Kroger Supermarket development located at the
intersection of Temple Avenue and Hamilton Avenue in Colonial Heights, Virginia is
documented in this Traffic Impact Analysis. The analyses contained in this document are
compliant with Virginia DOT (VDOT) guidelines and are necessitated by the rezoning of the site
due to Virginia Legislative Code Chapter 527 Regulations. These regulations require that all
rezoning cases be evaluated for traffic impacts when meeting certain criteria in terms of trip
generation or location. This site meets both the trip generation requirements and the location
requirements as the site will generate more than the required trips per day for evaluation and it
also located adjacent to the Interstate 95 ramp terminal at Temple Avenue. Therefore traffic
analyses were undertaken for the existing (2013) year, Opening Year (2015) and Horizon Year
(2021). For 2013 and 2015 the existing conditions were analyzed with and without the site
constructed and the results compared to quantify the impact. The same analysis was
performed for 2021, however, the existing conditions were adjusted to incorporate the
proposed Interstate 95 Interchange Improvement Project at Temple Avenue which includes
shift the existing ramp terminal intersection west to the location of the existing bridges over
the CSX Railroad. As part of this shift, the new ramp terminal intersection is currently planned
on being constructed as a multi-lane roundabout with bypass lanes.
The results of the analysis indicate that the proposed Supermarket would be expected to
impact the traffic operations of the Study Area. Based on the analysis presented in this report,
the following trip generation, traffic observations and improvements are proposed as a result of
The development is expected to generate approximately 8,720 vehicle trips per day with
approximately 230 AM peak hour trips and approximately 520 PM peak hour trips.

Kroger Supermarket R550 – Traffic Impact Analysis
The proposed Kroger Supermarket R550 development is located on approximately 9.5 acres of
land on the southeast corner of Route 144 (Temple Avenue) and Hamilton Avenue in Colonial
Heights, Virginia, as shown in Figure 1. The development is planned to include an 86,792
square foot Kroger supermarket and a 9-pump Kroger fueling station.
The proposed site is currently occupied with the City of Colonial Heights courthouse and zoned
as RO (Residential Office). The City of Colonial Heights is proposing a rezoning of the site to GB
(General Business) to accommodate the new supermarket and fueling station as part of an
existing Development Agreement with Kroger Mid-Atlantic. Land surrounding this site is
developed with a mixture of land uses, but mostly residential uses and the site is bounded on
the east by the Interstate 95 ramps.
The purpose of this study is to estimate the overall traffic impacts associated with the proposed
Kroger Supermarket R550 development and to identify any resultant roadway and traffic
control improvements required to handle the site traffic. This study will analyze the impacts of
the development for the anticipated opening in 2015, and approximately six years following
construction (2021) as agreed upon by the developer and Virginia Department of
Transportation (VDOT) during the Pre-Scoping Meeting in September 2013 and based on the
A crucial element to this study is the fact that VDOT is planning an I-95 Interchange
Improvement Project which includes the proposed replacement of the traffic signal at Temple
Avenue and the I-95 ramps with a 2-lane roundabout located approximately 400-500’ west of
the existing signalized ramp intersection. This study will incorporate the planned roundabout
into the analysis of the development. Based on the proposed construction timeframe noted in
the Virginia DOT Six-Year Improvement Plan (SYIP), this construction is not likely to be

The existing roadway facilities adjacent to the project site are Temple Avenue and Hamilton
Avenue. Temple Avenue is a four-lane divided east-west arterial north of the site. The roadway
is classified as an Urban Minor Arterial west of I-95 and an Urban Other Principle Arterial east of
I-95. The posted speed limit on Temple Avenue is 35 miles per hour (mph).
Hamilton Avenue is a two-lane undivided north-south roadway, west of the site. The roadway
serves as a collector for the residential area bounded by Temple Avenue, Route 1/301
(Boulevard) and I-95. Hamilton Avenue is signalized at Temple Avenue. The posted speed limit
Peak hour traffic volumes were collected at the following ten intersections within the study
Figure 2 illustrates the existing peak hour traffic volumes collected and balanced to account for
any data collection anomalies. The traffic count data are included in Appendix A.
Intersection operations were evaluated using the existing peak hour traffic volumes and the
existing intersection lane geometry and traffic control. The analysis software output
worksheets are included in Appendix B. Intersection capacity analyses were performed
utilizing techniques consistent with the 2010 Highway Capacity Manual (HCM) from Synchro
traffic analysis software (Version 8, Build 804, Revision 795) for the signalized and unsignalized
intersections. The results are a level-of-service (LOS) rating, which is a qualitative assessment of
the traffic flow characteristics described by a letter designation ranging from A to F, with LOS A
representing the best possible operating conditions and LOS F representing congested
conditions. Unsignalized capacity analysis produces an LOS result only for each yielding vehicle
movement since free-flowing movements are not constrained. Signalized intersection capacity
analysis produces an LOS result for each movement, approach and the overall intersection.

Site access is proposed along Temple Avenue and Hamilton Avenue. The Temple Avenue access
is planned as a right-in/right-out access for the opening in 2015; however, access to Ridge Road
will remain unchanged from Temple. It should be noted, however, that with the roundabout
construction completion at the I-95 Interchange Improvement Project, Ridge Road will be
shifted to the intersection of Temple Avenue and Hamilton Avenue and this median opening
fully removed. The second site access, located off of Hamilton Avenue, will provide a full
movement access to the development in accordance with VDOT’s Access Management
guidelines found in the VDOT Road Design Manual Appendix F.
The calculation of trips was based on trip generation rates given in the Institute of
Transportation Engineers (ITE) Trip Generation Manual, 9th Edition. The trip generation and
subsequent analyses for the supermarket and fueling station are based on typical weekday AM
and PM commuting peak hour conditions.
Pass-by trip generation reductions were applied to both the supermarket and fueling station
within the site development. Pass-by trips represent traffic that would already be traveling on
the adjacent roadways, regardless of whether the proposed project site was developed.

The following mitigation measures were applied to improve the traffic operations surrounding
the proposed Kroger Supermarket R550 site.
At the intersection of the Boulevard and Temple Avenue, the single southbound left
turn lane was replaced with double left turn lanes with storage lengths of 250 feet. An
additional northbound right turn lane was also added with a storage length of 100 feet.
It should be noted that the additional left turning accommodations will be required
based on the expected growth rate of traffic by 2021 regardless of installation of the
site. However, for the purposes of the mitigation measures, it was assumed that this
project will be included in the future year networks, although at this it is not
At the intersection of Temple Avenue and Hamilton Avenue, the single westbound left
turn lane was replaced with double left turn lanes with storage lengths of 250 feet and
southbound Hamilton Avenue was given an additional receiving lane that terminated as
a left turn lane at the new site access. A northbound left turn lane with a storage length
of 100 feet was also added to the intersection.
The analysis of the total traffic volumes at Temple Avenue and Hamilton Avenue shows
operational deficiencies and significant westbound left queue lengths with the existing
signalized intersection. It was briefly examined whether the intersection would perform better
with a traffic signal or a roundabout. A footprint for a roundabout with a minimum 158-foot
inscribed circle diameter with 16-foot lanes was used for planning. The configuration of the
roundabout is shown in Figure 13. With a traffic signal, the intersection would require double
left turn lanes in the westbound direction, an additional receiving lane for southbound
Hamilton Avenue and a left turn lane in the northbound direction. With these improvements,
the intersection would operate with a LOS C during the PM peak hour. The roundabout option
provides an overall LOS A for the intersection with all movements operating at a LOS C or better
with less overall queuing, especially in the eastbound direction, however the footprint required
for the implementation of the roundabout makes it cost-prohibitive when compared to the
upgrades needed for the signalized intersection. Therefore, it is recommended that the Temple
Avenue and Hamilton Avenue intersection remain signalized.
The proposed intersection lane configurations are shown in Figures 16 and 17.
